{{nihongo|'''Hakuo Yanagisawa'''|Êü≥Ê≤¢ ‰ºØÂ§´|Yanagisawa Hakuo|extra= August 18, 1935, in [[Fukuroi, Shizuoka]]|lead=yes}} was the [[Minister of Health, Labour and Welfare (Japan)|Minister of Health, Labour and Welfare]] in [[Japan]] (2006‚Äì2007). He is a member of the [[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)|Liberal Democratic Party]] and a member of the [[House of Representatives of Japan|House of Representatives]]. His constituency is [[Shizuoka Prefecture]] 3rd District.

In January 2007, he drew criticism for describing women as "birth-giving machines" and "baby making devices" in a speech on the falling [[birthrate]] of Japan.<ref>[[The Guardian]]: ''[https://www.theguardian.com/japan/story/0,,2001056,00.html Japanese minister wants 'birth-giving machines', aka women, to have more babies]'' (Justin McCurry in Tokyo dated January 29, 2007)</ref><ref>[[BBC]] News: ''[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/6306685.stm Japan women called child machines]'' (27 January 2007, 22:48 GMT)</ref> He said later "it was extremely sound to have more than two children".<ref>Japan Times: ''[http://www.japantimes.co.jp/text/nn20070208a2.html Yanagisawa apologizes anew, adds gaffe]''(8 February 2007)</ref>

He believes in [[Tenrikyo]].<ref>http://www.jcp.or.jp/akahata/aik07/2007-04-09/2007040914_01_0.html</ref>

== Career ==
He is from the city of [[Fukuroi, Shizuoka|Fukuroi]] in [[Shizuoka Prefecture]].{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} He graduated from the Faculty of Law at the [[University of Tokyo]] in 1961.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} In 1980 he was elected to the [[House of Representatives of Japan|House of Representatives]] for the first time, and has been elected eight times since. He was the [[Parliamentary Secretary for Foreign Affairs]] from July 1994 until August 1995, and the Chairman of the Committee on Health and Welfare from March 1998 to July 1998.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}

In July 1998 he was appointed to be the Minister of State for the [[National Land Agency]] by [[Prime Minister of Japan|Prime Minister]] [[Keiz≈ç Obuchi]], and became the Minister of State for Financial Reconstruction in October of that year.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} He was the Minister of State and Chairman of the [[Financial Reconstruction Commission]] from December 1998 to October 1999. He then reprised that role from December 2000 to January 2001.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} He was the Minister of State for Financial Services from January 2001 to September 2002, when he stepped down due to a disagreement with the minister in charge of [[economic policy|economic]] and [[fiscal policy]], [[Heiz≈ç Takenaka]].<ref>''[http://www.japantimes.co.jp/cabinet/cabinet_profiles_g.html The Japan Times Online Cabinet Profiles - Hakuo Hanagisawa]'' (27 January 2007, 22:48 GMT)</ref>  He was the Chairman of the Research Commission on the Tax System for the [[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)|LDP]] from November 2005 to September 2006. He became the [[Minister of Health, Labour and Welfare (Japan)|Minister of Health, Labour and Welfare]] in September 2006.<ref>''[http://www.kantei.go.jp/foreign/abedaijin/060926/07yanagisawa_e.html Minister of Health, Labour and Welfare]'' (27 January 2007, 22:48 GMT)</ref> He is a member of the [[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)|Liberal Democratic Party]], belonging specifically to the ''K≈çchikai'' (''Koga'' faction).

