{{About|the Hungarian Native Faith movement|other modern Pagan religions in Hungary|Neopaganism in Hungary}}
[[File:Cross-lorraine.svg|thumb|150px|[[Two-barred cross]]es symbolise the [[tree of life]] in Hungarian Native Faith.]]
The '''Hungarian Native Faith''' ([[Hungarian language|Hungarian]]: ''≈êsmagyar Vall√°s''), also termed '''Hungarian Neopaganism''', is a [[modern Paganism|modern Pagan]] [[new religious movement]] aimed at representing an [[ethnic religion]] of the [[Hungarian people|Hungarians]], inspired by [[t√°ltos|taltosism]] (Hungarian shamanism), [[Hungarian mythology|ancient mythology]] and [[shamanistic remnants in Hungarian folklore|later folklore]]. The Hungarian Native Faith movement has roots in 18th- and 19th-century [[Age of Enlightenment|Enlightenment]] and [[Romanticism|Romantic]] elaborations, and early-20th-century ethnology.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|pp=230‚Äì231}} The construction of a national Hungarian religion was endorsed in interwar [[Hungarian Turanism|Turanist]] circles (1930s‚Äì1940s), and, eventually, Hungarian Native Faith movements blossomed in [[Hungary]] after the fall of the [[Soviet Union]].{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|pp=36‚Äì62}}

The boundaries between Hungarian Native Faith groups are often traced along their differing ideas about the [[ethnogenesis|ethnogenetic]] origins of the Hungarians, which have historically been a matter of debate.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=66}} Many organisations acknowledge the commonly accepted theory that Hungarians originated among the [[Uralic peoples]]. Other Hungarian Native Faith groups, however, cultivate further links with [[Scythian]], [[Sumer]]ian,{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|pp=37‚Äì38}} [[Turkic peoples|Turkic]]{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|pp=43‚Äì47}} and other cultures.

Besides the elaborations developed within intellectual circles, the grassroots development of the Hungarian Native Faith largely relies upon the work of individual [[shaman]]s or [[neoshamanism|neoshamans]], the ''t√°ltos'', whom have become popular in Hungary since the 1980s.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|pp=36‚Äì62}} Some Hungarian Native Faith organisations are supported by political parties of the right-wing, including [[Fidesz]] and [[Jobbik]].{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|pp=64‚Äì65}}

==Overview and essential features==
[[File:T√°ltos (1).jpg|thumb|Ritual performed at the Temple of the Seven Images of the Mother of God.]]
===Roots of the Hungarian Native Faith===
Since the eighteenth and the nineteenth centuries, throughout the [[Age of Enlightenment|Enlightenment]] and especially [[Romanticism]], the study of the ancient religion of the Hungarians has been tied together with the debate about their [[ethnogenesis]] and the nature of [[Hungarian language|their language]].{{sfnm|1a1=Kolozsi|1y=2012|1p=37|2a1=Szil√°rdi|2y=2013|2pp=230‚Äì231}} This kaleidoscopic search for the origins of the Hungarians has continued to be productive well into the twentieth century, especially as a means to build a strong national identity. According to scholars, this search was fueled by the experience of the Hungarians under foreign powers, namely the [[Austria-Hungary|Austrian]] and [[Hungarian Soviet Republic|Soviet]] dominations.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=231}} The theme of a national Hungarian religion was also dear to [[Hungarian Turanism|Hungarian Turanist]] circles in the 1930s and the 1940s, who looked for evidences to demonstrate a kinship between the [[Uralic peoples|Uralic]] and [[Turkic peoples]], and generally the origins of these "[[Turan]]ian" populations in [[Central Asia]].{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|pp=43‚Äì47}} The Protestant priest B√©la Murak√∂zy, writing in 1921, forebode that Turanism, with its anti-Western slants and its fascination with the Orient, would have taken a religious direction trying to resurrect "ancient paganism".{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=47}} When Hungary was occupied by [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] forces in 1945, many Turanists emigrated to Western countries and continued to work there on their ideas, to reintroduce them to Hungary starting in the 1990s, after the collapse of the Soviet Union.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=48}}

Theories about [[Scythian]] and [[Sumer]]ian origins were supported by many Turanist ethnologists.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=38}} At the turn of the twentieth century, the first to popularise the notion of a [[Turanian languages|Turanian linguistic family]] inclusive of Hungarian and Sumerian was Gyula Ferenczy.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|pp=232‚Äì234}} In the post-war period, a direct filiation of the Hungarians from the Sumerians was theorised by Tibor Bar√°th, Victor Pad√°nyi, Andr√°s Zakar,{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|pp=232‚Äì234}} and especially Ida Bobula, though the most well-known supporter of the theory is Ferenc Badinyi-J√≥s, who emigrated to Argentina, according to whom the original undivided Sumerian-Hungarian ethnicity was based on the [[Carpathian Mountains]].{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|pp=50‚Äì52}} The theory has left a lasting influence in the Hungarian Native Faith movement, as Badinyi-J√≥s was among the first to propose the constitution of an ethnic "Hungarian Church".{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=53}} Other scholars proposed the kinship of the Hungarians with [[Hebrews]], [[Persian people|Persians]], [[ancient Egypt]]ians, and others even with [[Japanese people|Japanese]], [[Chinese people|Chinese]], [[Greeks]], and other peoples.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|pp=230‚Äì231}}

Already in 1770, J√°nos Sajnovics demonstrated the relationship of Hungarian with [[Uralic languages]], with the publication of the ''Demonstratio idioma Ungarorum et Lapponum idem esse''.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=231}} In the nineteenth century, with new studies on folklore, academic circles welcomed the idea that ancient Hungarian religion was essentially [[shamanism|shamanic]], related to Uralic and [[Siberia]]n traditions. In the meantime, Arnold Ipolyi, bishop of [[Oradea]], published his monumental work ''Magyar Mythol√≥gia'' (''Hungarian Mythology''), finished in 1854, aimed at matching the [[Brothers Grimm]]'s ''Deutsche Mythologie''.{{sfnm|1a1=Kolozsi|1y=2012|1p=38|2a1=Szil√°rdi|2y=2013|2p=231}}

In the 1960s, M√°ty√°s Jen≈ë Feh√©r, another emigrant to Argentina who was a church-historian and former [[Dominican Order|Dominican]], provided a seminal view for a post-Christian Hungary. From 1967, he published several books about the ''Kassai K√≥dex'' or ''Collectio Dominicana''. He claimed that in 1944 he had found in Kosice a previously unknown medieval codex with records from inquisition courts. The codex documented a centuries-long effort by the merciless Christian church to exterminate the taltoses, Hungarian shamans, the representatives of the pre-Christian Hungarian religion whose role was to preserve the integrity of the nation. Though it is considered a forgery by academic scholarship, the document is among the reference points for proponents of the Hungarian Native Faith to illustrate the high morality of the indigenous religion and of its representatives.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|pp=52‚Äì53}}

===Taltosism===
"Taltosism" is Hungarian shamanism, practised by the ''[[t√°ltos]]'' (English plural "taltoses"{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|loc=passim}}), that is to say Hungarian shamans, and is an essential element of the Hungarian Native Faith. Hungarian chronicles of the 13th century still reported about "magicians" (taltoses) who practised their rites for the welfare of society.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=39}} Hungarian taltosism persisted until the [[World War II]] in rural areas, where certain people were still considered taltoses by the local communities, though they practiced weather-magic only.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=39}}

Ideas about an ethnic Hungarian shamanism as a defining characteristic of the Hungarian essence were studied within a [[psychoanalysis|psychoanalytic]] framework by G√©za R√≥heim in the 1920s, and later by Vilmos Di√≥szegi with field work in Siberia in the 1950s and the 1960s.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=38}} The shamanic character of the original Hungarian religion is accepted by most contemporary scholars, and has been the focus of most new studies.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|pp=38‚Äì39}}

====Study of the taltoses====
Di√≥szegi described taltoses as specialists who are able of going through a controlled ecstasy (''rejtez√©s'').{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=40}} One becomes a taltos by heredity or vocation, and the process of becoming one includes the typical stages of psychophysical disease, acceptance and healing: After an initial resistance to vocation and the various symptoms of the "shamanic disease", the chosen by the gods finally accepts his role and is endowed with his powers.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=40}} Taltoses acquire superior knowledge at a young age‚Äîusually at seven‚Äî, through shamanic journeys taking place in days-long dreams, in which the main goal is to climb the ''[[√©gig √©r≈ë fa]]'' ("sky-high tree"), also called ''√©let fa'' ("[[tree of life]]"), ''vil√°g fa'' ("[[world tree]]") or ''tetejetlen fa'' ("tree without a top").{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=40}} Di√≥szegi considered many elements of Hungarian taltosism to be peculiar to the Hungarian ethnicity, not to be found in Central Asian shamanic traditions.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=40}} He described the role of the taltos as the "recognition and accomplishment of things required by the community, but unresolved due to the limitation of its own [the community's] powers".{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=235}}

Contemporary Hungarian religious studies, primarily the academic circle revolving around Mih√°ly Hopp√°l, has acquired an important role for the international study of shamanism.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=41}} The Hungarian ethnological discourse presents taltoses, and shamans in general, as those whose socio-religious role is to heal, prophesise, and keep the integrity of cultural traditions by connecting the past and the present and thus projecting into the future, integrating the individual and the community, mankind and the gods.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=41}} In the words of Hopp√°l, shamanism is depicted as a "bridge and symbol, because it interconnects the traditions of the past with the present, and anchors the future of traditions".{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=41}} The shaman's tasks are "leading the community, guarding the ethnic consciousness, being a (sacrificial) priest".{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=235}}

====Modern taltosism====
[[File:T√°ltos (2).jpg|thumb|A modern taltos performing a ritual with his drum, in front of a fire.]]
The modern taltos movement started in the 1980s, developing links with [[Michael Harner]] and other representatives of [[core shamanism]] from the [[United States]] since 1986.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=42}} However, there are significant differences between American [[neoshamanism]] and Hungarian modern taltosism. While the American movement aims at representing a trans-cultural technique, designed as adaptable to different cultural contexts, and focused on self-empowerment and healing application, Hungarian taltosism is first and foremost an [[ethnic religion|ethnic religious]] technique.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|pp=42‚Äì43}} Mih√°ly Hopp√°l supported the taltos revival in his country as a means for consolidating a Hungarian Native Faith, and therefore for ethnic rejuvenation.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|pp=41‚Äì42}}

Congregations of taltoses and their followers hold weekly ritual and healing gatherings, and they organise pilgrimages to holy sites. Rituals practised by Hungarian Native Faith practitioners include rituals of initiation and passage, and rituals for fertility, healing and purification, either for the environment, the community of believers, or the entire Hungarian nation. They may involve sweat lodges, fire-walk, drumming, and techniques of meditation.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=61}} While the ceremonies are usually led by taltoses, the community of believers is actively involved.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=61}}

Among well-known modern taltoses there are Zolt√°n Nagy S√≥lyomfi, Istv√°n Somogyi, Feh√©rholl√≥ √ñsk√º, and Andr√°s Kov√°cs-Magyar.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=61}} Other mediators of the tradition are Imr√© M√°t√©, Attila Heffner, Tam√°s Hervay, and G√°bor Szemz≈ë.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=235}} Although they belong to different organisations, they agree on the [[monotheism]] of Hungarian Native Faith's theology and on the role of the taltos. According to them, the taltos functions as "the bridge between the celestial and the earthly worlds, between the irrational and the rational, the endless and the finite". Taltoses are interpreters of the transcendent.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=235}}

According to Attila Heffner's definition:{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=235}}
{{Quote|Taltoses opened up, expanded their consciousness to this world, which is not perceivable in a normal state of the mind. During the so-called soul-journey ... they brought answers to questions, healing to diseases, seeing events of past and future, with the help of a purposive, goal-oriented action in this broader horizon of the existing world.}}

Taltoses share their knowledge acting as instructors, teaching their ideas in organised frameworks (for instance S√≥lyomfi's School of the Ancient Source or Kov√°cs' Taltos School), through lectures or in discussion circles. The techniques for getting in touch with the transcendent (''r√©v√ºl√©s'') take place through an active participation in ceremonies and rituals. Taltoses are religious specialists, and their role of healers is particularly pronounced; for instance, exercises of directed meditation, induced by drumming, to eliminate harmful thoughts, play a prominent role in their practice.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=235}}

In their responsibility for the entire nation, and their role as keepers and awakeners of the national essence, modern taltoses often claim connection with the royal [[√Årp√°d dynasty|House of √Årp√°d]]‚Äîthe first dynasty to rule Hungary‚Äîand with [[Jesus]], reinterpreted as a shamanic figure. According to Attila Heffner:{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=236}}
{{Quote|[While] the shamanic quality is characteristic of the system of universal human culture, ... the taltos is specifically the guardian and executive of the Hun, Sz√©kely and Hungarian human world and traditions. Whereas a shaman can be a member of any culture ... a taltos pronouncedly exists in accordance with the spirituality of our Hungarian culture saturated in the appreciation of Jesus.}}

===Scriptures===
Within the Hungarian Native Faith movement, two mythopoetic texts have become the bases of two concurrent streams of religious doctrine. These texts are the ''Arvisura'' written by Zolt√°n Pa√°l, and the ''Yotengrit'' four-books collection written by Imre M√°t√©.{{sfn|Hubbes|2013|p=229}} Mythopoetic themes from both the works have more recently been synthesised in other media, such as the long animated film ''Sons of Heaven'' (''Az √âg Ô¨Åai'', 2010).{{sfn|Hubbes|2013|p=226, note 10}} Another long animation influenced by Hungarian Native Faith narratives, this time based on ethnographic and historical data from the Uralic paradigm and realised with subsidy from the national government, is the ''Song of the Miraculous Hind'' (''√ânek a csodaszarvasr√≥l'', 2002).{{sfn|Hubbes|2013|pp=226‚Äì227}}

Zolt√°n Pa√°l (1913‚Äì1982) was a steelworker who, during the [[World War II|Second World War]], was initiated by a Siberian [[Mansi people|Mansi]] shaman named Tura Salavare, whom was then soldier in the [[Red Army]]. Pa√°l compiled the knowledge he acquired in the ''Arvisura'', which tells the history of the [[Huns|Hunnish]] tribes starting from a mythical prehistory, to their settling of [[Mesopotamia]] and then [[Ordos culture|Ordos]], and finally to [[Matthias Corvinus]]. The book draws elements from [[Finno-Ugric peoples|Finno-Ugric]] traditions.{{sfn|Hubbes|2013|pp=229‚Äì230}}

The ''Yotengrit'' is more religious-philosophical in its message. Its author Imre M√°t√© was the taltos, or ''b√°csa'', founder of the Yotengrit Church. The work claims to represent the faithful transmission of the ancient knowledge preserved by people in the R√°bak√∂z region of western Hungary, the heritage of the so-called "B√º√ºn-religion", the persecuted original faith of the Hungarians. The work and especially the ''Prophecy of Nyirka'' which it contains, an allegorical text supposed to forebode the future of Hungary and global politics, has become a stronghold for nationalism and far-right occultism.{{sfn|Hubbes|2013|pp=230‚Äì231}}

==Hungarian Native Faith churches==
There are a variety of Hungarian Native Faith churches reflecting the movement's internal diversity. These churches differ from each other in both their doctrines and the character of their activities.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=59}} They often develop from local taltos-led communities, or are individually established by a taltos. These taltoses are considered by their followers valid spiritual leaders and while some practise only within the boundaries of their local communities, others have acquired a national reputation.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|pp=60‚Äì61}} Their popular acknowledgement depends on attributed ritual and healing efficacy.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|pp=60‚Äì61}}

There are churches which base their doctrines on an outspoken synthesis of different traditions, and churches which claim to represent purely native traditions.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|pp=238‚Äì239}} In the first group there are the Church of Esoteric Doctrines (''Ezoterikus Tanok Egyh√°za'') or Church of the Holy Crown (''Szent Korona Egyh√°z'')‚Äîfounded in 1996 and officially registered by the Hungarian state in 1997‚Äî,{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=238}} the Church of the Universe (''Univerzum Egyh√°za'') of Gi√∂rgy P√©ter P√°l Kisfaludy, and the Ancient Hungarian Taltos Church of Andr√°s Kov√°cs.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=239}} Most of the others fall within the second category, including the Community of Hungarian Religion of Attila Kov√°cs, the Ancient Hungarian Church of L√°szl√≥ Hjad√∫ Nimr√≥d, the Yotengrit Church of Imre M√°t√©, the Firebird Taltos Drum Circle of Zolt√°n S√≥lyomfi, the People of √Årp√°d Drumming Circle of Lehel Bakonyi, and the Traditional Church of the Order of √Årp√°d.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|pp=239‚Äì244}} The most influential among them have been the Yotengrit Church and the Ancient Hungarian Taltos Church.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=59}}

Besides these taltos-led groups there are taltoses who do not have a community and yet are regarded as the most charismatic figures of Hungarian Native Faith. They include Attila Heffner, Tam√°s Hervay the "Soul-Lifting Taltos", and J√°nos Majercsik Oguz.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=244}}

===Andr√°s Kov√°cs' Ancient Hungarian Taltos Church===
[[File:Szellemi T√°ltos Iskola gate.jpg|thumb|Gateway of the Noetic Taltos School.]]
The Ancient Hungarian Taltos Church (''≈êsmagyar T√°ltos Egyh√°z'') founded by Andr√°s Kov√°cs, a disciple of Kisfaludy, teaches a Hungarian Native Faith doctrine which it claims to be the original religion of the Huns. According to the church, God the Father is an energetic vibration which incarnated in a host, the Mother of God, begetting the Sun God (of whom Jesus is a representation).{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=239}} The [[Pilis Mountains]] are a holy place according to the Ancient Hungarian Taltos Church.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=59}} Kov√°cs is also the founder and director of the Noetic Taltos School (''Szellemi T√°ltos Iskola'').{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=59}}

===Attila Kov√°cs' Community of the Hungarian Religion===
The Community of the Hungarian Religion (''Magyar Vall√°s K√∂z√∂ss√©ge'') inherits those scholarly studies of the nineteenth century which claimed that Hungarian and [[Sumerian language]] share an origin in the hypothetical Turanian linguistic family. Based on these ideas, in the 1930s Zolt√°n Bencsi founded the Turanian Monotheist Movement. After [[Mikl√≥s Horthy]]'s government banned the organisation, some members went abroad. Among them was √ìtto J√°nos Homonnay, who in the 1960s, in [[Canada]], established the Hungarian Turul Society to promote the Turanist theses. In 1979, after Homonnay's death, J√°nos P√°ll took over the leadership of the group.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=240}}

The Community of Hungarian Religion was founded in Hungary in 1992 as a continuation of the Turul Society. The current leader is Attila Kov√°cs, according to whom the church already had gathered around one thousand members in the late 1990s. The church is distinctively anti-Christian, and considers the adoption of Christianity by [[Stephen I of Hungary|King Stephen I]] in 1000 CE a disaster which brought about the destruction of authentic Hungarian religious culture.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=240}} The church endorses the hypothesis of the kinship of Hungarians and Sumerians, and supports the use of the [[Old Hungarian alphabet]] instead of the Latin script.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=240}}

===Imre M√°t√©'s Yotengrit Church===
The Yotengrit Church (''Yotengrit Egyh√°z''), whose complete name is the Church of the Ancient Spirit of the Endless Sea (''Tengerv√©gtelen ≈ês-Szellem Egyh√°za''), was founded around 2007 by Imre M√°t√©. He, whose title in the organisation was ''b√°csa'' ("master"), emigrated to Germany in 1956, during the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956|revolution]] against the communist government of the [[Hungarian People's Republic]] in which he participated. While in Germany, he worked as a businessman and poet, but returned to Hungary in the 2000s to spend his last years in [[B√°gyogszov√°t]].{{sfnm|1a1=Kolozsi|1y=2012|1p=90|2a1=Szil√°rdi|2y=2013|2p=241}} He founded the Yotengrit Church as the representative of the ancient Hungarian religion, the so-called "B√º√ºn-religion", passed down through the unwritten tradition of the ''tud√≥'' ("knower") people along the [[Raba (river)|Raba]] river. M√°t√© published a series of nine books, entitled ''Yotengrit'', in which he explained theology and linguistic etymology.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=241}} In recent years, the Yotengrit Church has become one of the most influential organisations of the Hungarian Native Faith. While it is considered by its adherents as a faithful heir of the pre-Christian Hungarian belief systems, it shows various non-indigenous influences.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=89}}

The theology of the Yotengrit Church emphasises a conception of primordial God, called ''Yotengrit'', ''Tengrit'' or ''[[Tengri]]'', which represents all the deities in their yet undivided state. In Hungarian the related word ''tenger'' means "sea", and represents such primordial undifferentiation. The primordial God then manifests as a male‚Äìfemale duality: Ukk√≥, the mother goddess whose forehead is decorated by the moon, and who is identified as the ''Boldogasszony'' (the "Blessed Lady") of Christianised folk beliefs; and G√∂n√ºz, the sun-faced father god.{{sfnm|1a1=Kolozsi|1y=2012|1pp=89‚Äì98|2a1=Szil√°rdi|2y=2013|2p=241}}

At the time of the foundation of the church, Imre M√°t√© proclaimed the importance of an all-encompassing conception of God:{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=241}}
{{Quote|In this Hungarian religion, it is very important that God is a very abstract concept; a spiritual power. He cannot be simply impersonated; whenever he was impersonated‚ÄîG√∂n√ºz, Ukk√≥ or Boldogasszony‚Äîit was always the result of human imagination.}}

At the same time, the theology emphasises a national god peculiar to the Hungarians, M√°-Tun, the deified hero of the folk tale entitled ''Feh√©rl√≥fia'' ("Son of the White Horse"), who was originally a totemic animal ancestor.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=241}} M√°-Tun is identified with the historical figure of [[Modu Chanyu|Maodu]], founder of the first [[Xiongnu]] empire, and according to M√°t√© also of the empire of the Huns.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=241}} The Yotengrit Church is politically neutral, but, as M√°t√©'s stated, its teachings may be a "source of sane, aggression-free national politics".{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=241}}

===L√°szl√≥ Nimr√≥d's Ancient Hungarian Church===
The Ancient Hungarian Church (''≈êsmagyar Egyh√°z''), whose Hungarian headquarters are located in [[Mogyor√≥d]], was first established in [[Budapest]] in the 1990 by L√°szl√≥ Hjad√∫ Nimr√≥d, and was officially registered in 1998.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=239}} Nimr√≥d spends most of the year in the [[United States]] and the church has international headquarters located in [[Los Angeles]].{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=239}} The doctrine of the Ancient Hungarian Church is a synthesis of ancient Hungarian, [[East Asian religions|East Asian]] and Christian beliefs, though all of them are claimed to be original Hungarian-Turanian beliefs.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=240}} The church has strict religious regulations. For instance, preachers have to wear white and purple clothes with folk patterns. They celebrate the major holidays of the Christian calendar, winter and summer solstice, national holidays and the birthdays of important Hungarian historical personages.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=240}}

===Zolt√°n S√≥lyomfi's Firebird Taltos Drum Circle===
The Firebird Taltos Drum Circle (''T≈±zmad√°r T√°ltos Dobk√∂r'') was founded in 2006 by Zolt√°n Nagy S√≥lyomfi, who also acted as the chief executive of the Yotengrit Church when it was registered by the government. He later left the Yotengrit Church for undisclosed internal disputes and, despite his wish to return, was not allowed to do so by M√°t√©.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=242}} The aim of the group is to revive ancient Hungarian spirituality, mediating it to society in modern forms, helping the individuals to understand themselves and thus healing the world tree, which manifests itself through the individuals.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=242}}

The theology of the Drum Circle is "based upon the ancient Hungarian conception of the world, which is the One (God) which incorporates everything that exists".{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=242}} S√≥lyomfi teaches that there are two worlds: One is the "manifest world" represented by the world tree, while the other one is the "unmanifested, unshaped space" which contains the "shared consciousness" of mankind.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=242}}

The Drum Circle emphasises practice over doctrine, including drumming, breathing and voice techniques.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=242}} The aim of these practices is to widen one's consciousness to understand the operations of the One, becoming like the One.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=242}} The group practises ritual ceremonies for birth, initiation, marriage, death and the feasts of the Yearly Round. The School of the Ancient Source (''≈êsforr√°s Iskola''), associated with the church, organises camps and pilgrimages.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=242}}

===Traditional Church of the Order of √Årp√°d===
The Traditional Church of the Order of √Årp√°d (''√Årp√°d Rendj√©nek Jogalapja Tradicion√°lis Egyh√°z'') was founded in 2009 and has its reference points in the Turanist emigree ideologists Adorj√°n Magyar and Victor Pad√°nyi, but it is also inspired by the [[Traditionalist School]], the [[Nouvelle Droite]] of [[Alain de Benoist]], and to the reconstructed [[Proto-Indo-European religion]].{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=60}}

===Gaffer Bolya's Nest===
The group named Bolyanest (Gaffer Bolya's Nest) was founded in 1979 by Gaffer Bolya, a teacher in vocational secondary school titled ''Bolyap√≥'' within the group itself. Bolya's starting aim was to provide a way of good life for his students, whom formed the original core members of the group. The centre of the movement is in Budapest, and it was registered by the government in 1999.{{sfn|Cs√°ji|2017|p=214}} It is considered amongst the most influential Hungarian Native Faith movements today, especially concerning the process of re-mythologisation of Hungarian history.{{sfn|Cs√°ji|2017|p=215}} The group was originally focused on [[nature religion]], while in the most recent decades its focus has shifted to the discourse about ethnic roots.{{sfn|Cs√°ji|2017|p=215}}

Bolya acts as the group's ceremonial leader. The group has a core membership of around one hundred people, but its influence reaches the thousands of people. They are mostly from Budapest's middle class, but there are also farmers, entrepreneurs and intellectuals. The average age is over fifty-five and most of them are highly educated. They outspokenly identify themselves as non-Christians, though they do not presume to be the continuators of a well-defined pre-Christian religion; rather, they consciously construct a new religion based on Hungarian folklore and elements from other cultures' indigenous religions.{{sfn|Cs√°ji|2017|p=215}} Sumerian culture has been one of the main sources, although other cultures are explored too; for instance, Sumerian prayers are sung together with Russian songs.{{sfn|Cs√°ji|2017|pp=219‚Äì220}} They regard some natural sites surrounding Budapest and farther localities such as [[S√≥sk√∫t]], [[Borsodgeszt]], and Bodrogk√∂z, as their holy places where to make pilgrimage.{{sfn|Cs√°ji|2017|p=218}}

A fundamental teaching of Bolya is the conceptual distinction between "order" and "system", which remains the core of Bolyanest's thought. The former, the order, defines the natural way of being of everything in nature; everything is interconnected and interdependent, and each single part has a role in its instinctual cooperation with the others. The latter, the system, defines unnatural and artificial superstructures which take shape in societies when individuals and groups are surrounded by growing webs of norms, and are gradually alienated from each other and from their natural contexts. Gaffer Bolya was likely inspired by his studies of [[Jean-Jacques Rousseau]]'s and [[Leo Tolstoy]]'s thought in the development of this vision.{{sfn|Cs√°ji|2017|p=216}}

==Identity and politics==
[[File:T√°ltos (4).jpg|thumb|Gathering of a Hungarian Native Faith group for the performance of a ritual. The two leading figures hold ritual spears with strips of cloth of the colours of the [[flag of Hungary]] tied near the tips.]]
===Nationalism and anti-multiculturalism===
Hungarian Native Faith groups generally put a great emphasis on the discourse about ethnic roots, which are re-mythologised. Many Hungarian Native Faith groups espouse [[nationalism|nationalistic]] political views and organise their communities in exclusive ways, exhibiting political intolerance. At the same time, [[pluralism (political theory)|pluralism]] and [[multiculturalism]] are viewed as disturbances which erode Hungarian identity.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=244}} The popularity of these stances is attributed by scholars to the abrupt fall of the [[Iron Curtain]], followed by spiritual vacuum and the perception of being invaded by a "multi-faceted cultural market", which created an identity crisis in post-Soviet countries.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=244}} In the case of Hungarian Native Faith groups, this resulted in a rejection of postmodern heterogeneity and a sacralisation of the national identity, in which language, religion and politics form a single entity.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=244}} Hungarian Native Faith groups see themselves as a core minority, amongst all Hungarians, which represents the quintessence of Hungarianness.{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=245}}

===Relationship with Christianity===
The relationship between Hungarian Native Faith and Christianity varies from church to church. Some Hungarian Native Faith groups use Christian themes and terminology in their own doctrines,{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=230}} or propose the incorporation of Christianity itself into the Hungarian Native Faith, such as in the case of groups developing in the wake of the teachings of Ferenc Badinyi-J√≥s.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=69 ff}} Others, like the Community of Hungarian Religion{{sfn|Szil√°rdi|2013|p=240}} and the Bolyanest, are instead outspokenly anti-Christian.{{sfn|Cs√°ji|2017|pp=215‚Äì216}}

A fundamental notion in Hungarian Native Faith is that each "nation" should have its own "faith", and a "Christian Hungary" represents an anomaly which needs to be rectified. This rectification should come from a liquidation of Christianity.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=101}} Even among those Hungarian Native Faith groups which nourish warm feelings towards Jesus, regarded as compatible with the indigenous religion, including the Yotengrit Church, the Christian religious institution as it developed after Jesus‚Äîthe so-called "[[Pauline Christianity]]"‚Äîis in any case perceived as a corrupt entity to be dismantled.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=95}} More in particular, among these groups it is [[Eastern Christianity]] to be valued as compatible with the indigenous religion, and to be considered closer to what Jesus intended, while [[Western Christianity]] (the forms which have historically been dominant in Hungary) is seen as its antithesis and as a deviant, evil teaching. In these groups, Jesus is reinterpreted as a powerful ancestor and shaman.{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=102}}

Within the Bolyanest, most of the members deem Christianity a [[superstition]] aimed at the control of people. Christian symbolic motifs such as the cross and the [[tree of life]] are considered, together with the sun and the moon, as symbols of natural pre-Christian religion which were appropriated by the Christian churches. The majority of believers regards Christianity as the force which eradicated this natural ancient knowledge, including original Hungarian religion, and as the force responsible for the [[disenchantment]] of the world.{{sfn|Cs√°ji|2017|pp=215‚Äì216}}

===Relationship with Central Asian Tengrism===
Those taltoses who espouse Turanist theories sometimes declare explicit affiliation with [[Tengrism]], the Turkic [[ethnic religion]].{{sfn|Kolozsi|2012|p=62}} This is the case of Zolt√°n S√≥lyomfi. These taltoses are generally characterised by their use of the Turkic name of God, ''[[Tengri]]'', instead of the Hungarian term ''Isten''.

In 2012 a nine-meters high ''√©let fa'' (tree of life) was donated by Hungarian Native Faith groups to the Tengrists of [[Kazakhstan]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Hongrie: le retour en force du n√©o-paganisme|url=http://www.hu-lala.org/2012/05/17/hongrie-le-retour-en-force-du-neo-paganisme/|website=Hulala|date=17 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120620135853/http://www.hu-lala.org/2012/05/17/hongrie-le-retour-en-force-du-neo-paganisme/|archive-date=20 June 2012}}</ref> In the same year, Ojun Adigzsi See-Oglu, a famous shaman from [[Tuva]], was invited to the [[Hungarian Parliament Building]] to perform a ritual dance around the [[Holy Crown of Hungary]] for the welfare of the Hungarian nation.<ref>{{cite web|last=Baumgartner|first=Vincent|title=Un chamane au secours de la Hongrie!|url=https://hu-lala.org/un-chamane-au-secours-de-la-hongrie/|website=Hulala|date=28 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150922184958/https://hu-lala.org/un-chamane-au-secours-de-la-hongrie/|archive-date=22 September 2015}}</ref>

