The Kachchhapaghatas of Gwalior are especially noted for their art and architecture.<ref name="Rahman_2012">{{cite journal |url=http://jhss.org/archivearticleview.php?artid=145 |title=Art of the KachchhapaghƒÅtas in Central India: An assessment |journal=Journal of History & Social Sciences |volume=3 |issue=2 |year=2012 |author=Rahman Ali }}</ref> Kachchhapaghata ruler Mahipala commissioned the [[Sas-Bahu Temple]] at Gwalior. Records of two grants issued by him at Gwalior, dated 1093 and 1104 CE, have been found. Several silver and gold coins issued by him have also been discovered.{{sfn|P. C. Roy|1980|pp=70-71}} Ajayapala (r. c. 1192‚Äì1194) had the Gangola tank of Gwalior desilted, as attested by a 1194 inscription.{{sfn|Mysore Ramsharma|p=133}}

Other temples constructed by the Gwalior branch include the ones located at:

